{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501612"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:30:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:30:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1771"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1771"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.1,0.29,0.04,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51173"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1771"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36445"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"125"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11582"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14476"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34681"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51173"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of lower back pain. The pain is dull and located in the lower lumbar region. Paracetamol provides slight relief. Over the last week, he has noticed changes in his urination, including increased frequency, urgency, and dysuria. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes and takes metformin regularly. He has never used recreational drugs. One year ago, he was involved in a motor vehicle accident but was discharged from physiotherapy with resolution of symptoms. He works as a removalist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is generalised lower back pain on palpation but no vertebral tenderness. Neurological examination of the lower limbs is normal, with no signs of saddle anaesthesia or bowel incontinence. Relevant blood tests have been ordered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate imaging investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No investigation required","Prostate MRI","Ultrasound of kidneys, ureters and bladder","Plain CT spine","MRI spine and back"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is consistent with an episode of non-spinal lower back pain, likely referred visceral pain secondary to acute bacterial prostatitis. The diagnosis can be made clinically and is supported by urinary changes including increased frequency, urgency, and dysuria, as well as a lack of neurological features. In this scenario, \u003Cstrong\u003Eno investigation\u003C/strong\u003E is required as the first step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProstate MRI\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as an initial investigation for suspected acute bacterial prostatitis. It may be considered in cases of chronic prostatitis or if there are concerns about prostatic abscess formation, but it is not appropriate in this acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of kidneys, ureters and bladder\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered for a longer course of urinary symptoms which may show evidence of chronic cystitis or pyelonephritis. However, this is not necessary in this acute scenario and would not be the first-line investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain CT spine\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI spine and back\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated in this case. Imaging of the spine is generally not recommended for acute lower back pain in the absence of red flag symptoms. This patient does not present with any alarm features such as neurological symptoms, history of cancer, intravenous drug use, or prolonged corticosteroid use that would warrant immediate imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that 90% of patients seen in primary care for lower back pain will have a mechanical or nonspecific aetiology. In the absence of red flags, there is no indication for radiological investigation. The patient should be managed with antibiotics for the suspected prostatitis and reviewed. Imaging would only be indicated if he fails to improve with antibiotics, with concerns for complications such as prostatic abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key learning point is that back pain in the absence of alarm symptoms and signs does not require any imaging. The focus should be on clinical assessment, appropriate management (in this case, likely antibiotics for prostatitis), and follow-up to ensure improvement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Back pain in the absence of alarm symptoms and signs does not require any imaging.","Acute bacterial prostatitis can present with lower back pain and urinary symptoms.","Mechanical or nonspecific aetiology accounts for 90% of lower back pain cases in primary care."],"references":["Henderson M, Tierney L, Smetana G. The Patient History. Second edition. McGraw-Hill; 2012.","Hall AM, Aubrey-Bassler K, Thorne B, Maher CG. Do not routinely offer imaging for uncomplicated low back pain. BMJ. 2021 Feb 12;372:n291. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33579691/","Coker TJ, Dierfeldt DM. Acute Bacterial Prostatitis: Diagnosis and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Jan 15;93(2):114-20. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26926407/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36445"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36445"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-21T20:09:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-21T20:11:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1771"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51173"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relatio